Cl.Cm: Internal unique identifier

A reporting unit is the geospatial area that is used to aggregate the water supply, withdrawal, or consumptive use. The ReportingUnitID is the unique identification number for the geospatial area. It could be a 5-digit FIPs code for a county, a 12-digit code for a HUC (or fewer digits), or a custom number created by the data provider. The data provider should concatenate their OrganizationID + custom identifier to ensure this number is unique.
the reporting unit native identifer in each memeber state

The reporting unit name. All HUCs and Counties have a name as part of a WaDE controlled vocabulary. If the reporting unit is a custom geospatial area, the data provider should include names wherever possible.
The type of reporting unit - county, HUC, or a custom delineation.
Date that the last reporting unit product version was released.
The reporting unit product version number. Could be a release of the HUC or County layer, or internal to the data provider.
Abbrieviated state identifier.
EPSG Code for projection, with a preference for WGS_1984, EPSG of 4326

This is a subcategorization of the aggregated variable. This allows the user to specify not only the general category of water data, but also a more specific categorization. For example, for a subcategorization of water supply, the variable would be [AggregatedWaterSupply, Reservoir]. For a subcategorization of water withdrawal, the variable would be [AggregatedWithdrawal, Irrigation]. Other examples: [AggregatedConsumptiveUse, Irrigation], [AggregatedReturnFlow, Discharge], etc.

This is a high-level variable used for site-specific water data. The general categories available are for water withdrawal, consumptive use, and return flow: [SiteSpecificWithdrawal], [SiteSpecificConsumptiveUse], [SiteSpecificReturnFlow]

GetSiteWaterAllocationData: Water Rights The brown tables are the dimensions tables (look us) that are mostly static over time.
The green table is the FACT table that changes over time and connects things together.
Purple tables are Controlled Vocabulary

GetSiteVariableData: site specific Use The brown tables are the dimensions tables (look us) that are mostly static over time. The green table is the FACT table that changes over time and connects things together.

GetAggVariableData: Aggregate use The brown tables are the dimensions tables (look us) that are mostly static over time. The green table is the FACT table that changes over time and connects things together.

GetAggRegulatoryOverlay: regulatory The brown tables are the dimensions tables (look us) that are mostly static over time. The green table is the FACT table that changes over time and connects things together.

The tables have identical fiels to faciliate their implementation in the next WaDE Master Controlled Vocabulary Registry similair to this one. http://vocabulary.wamdam.org/
